    <text id="B0342T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Hall asks Jackson to give his opinion on several cases being forwarded him by
                    Hall, one of which involves a stolen horse. </p>
            </div1>
        </front>

        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">T.P. Jackson</name>
                </head>

                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1867-08-13"><abbr expan="August">Aug.</abbr> 13t 1867</date>
                        <name type="place">Woodstock, <abbr expan="Virginia">Va</abbr></name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>

                <p>May I ask you to investigate the enclosed letters, sending me a separate
                    statement in each case.</p>

                <p>You see I take advantage of your kind offer. Please return as soon as possible.</p>

                <p>How do you get along in Augusta. Hope to see you soon.</p>

                <closer>
                    <salute>Respects</salute>
                    <signed>J.T.H. Hall<lb/><abbr expan="Lieutenant">Lt.</abbr> &amp;c</signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">P.S. Please see D. Fultz, who has a voucher in the name
                        of W. Shutters from M E Price of Staunton for one horse taken by Price for
                        which Shutters brought suit please send me a full report of same &amp;
                        state your opinion as to the justice of claim. If Price will settle it
                        without a trial you can arrange it with him. J.H.</seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
